&lt;h1&gt;X Marks the Spot: Mastering Systems of Equations by Graphing&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;Have you ever wondered how GPS knows exactly where you are, or how two airplanes avoid crashing in the sky? The secret is something called &lt;strong&gt;Systems of Equations&lt;/strong&gt;. Today, we are going to become math detectives and learn how to find the &amp;ldquo;treasure&amp;rdquo; (the solution) using nothing but a graph.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;🕵️ The Math Mystery: The Hiker’s Crossing&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="-the-math-mystery-the-hikers-crossing"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#-the-math-mystery-the-hikers-crossing" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Imagine two hikers, Alex and Sam, are exploring a forest.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Alex&lt;/strong&gt; starts at a base camp 2 miles North of the park entrance and walks steadily North (&lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;span class="katex-mathml"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;y = x + 2&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"&gt;&lt;span class="base"&gt;&lt;span class="strut" style="height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right:0.03588em;"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.2778em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mrel"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.2778em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="base"&gt;&lt;span class="strut" style="height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord mathnormal"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.2222em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mbin"&gt;+&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.2222em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="base"&gt;&lt;span class="strut" style="height:0.6444em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord"&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sam&lt;/strong&gt; starts at the entrance but walks much faster than Alex (&lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;span class="katex-mathml"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;y = 2x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"&gt;&lt;span class="base"&gt;&lt;span class="strut" style="height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right:0.03588em;"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.2778em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mrel"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.2778em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="base"&gt;&lt;span class="strut" style="height:0.6444em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord"&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord mathnormal"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Question:&lt;/strong&gt; If they both keep walking in straight lines, will their paths ever cross? If so, where exactly will they meet?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In algebra, Alex and Sam are two different equations. The point where they meet is called the &lt;strong&gt;Intersection Point&lt;/strong&gt;, and it is the &amp;ldquo;treasure&amp;rdquo; we are looking for!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;🗺️ The Master Method: Solving by Graphing&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="-the-master-method-solving-by-graphing"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#-the-master-method-solving-by-graphing" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Solving by graphing is the most visual way to &amp;ldquo;see&amp;rdquo; the answer. Think of it as drawing a map to a meeting point. Here is your 3-step detective manual:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Step 1: Get into Slope-Intercept Form&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="step-1-get-into-slope-intercept-form"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#step-1-get-into-slope-intercept-form" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Before you draw, make sure both equations look like &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;span class="katex-mathml"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;m&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;y = mx + b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"&gt;&lt;span class="base"&gt;&lt;span class="strut" style="height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right:0.03588em;"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.2778em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mrel"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.2778em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="base"&gt;&lt;span class="strut" style="height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord mathnormal"&gt;m&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord mathnormal"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.2222em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mbin"&gt;+&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.2222em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="base"&gt;&lt;span class="strut" style="height:0.6944em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord mathnormal"&gt;b&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div align="center"&gt;
&lt;svg width="350" height="120" viewBox="0 0 350 120" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" role="img" aria-label="Slope-intercept form with labels for slope and y-intercept"&gt;&lt;defs&gt;&lt;marker id="arrowhead-systems-blog" markerWidth="10" markerHeight="7" refX="0" refY="3.5" orient="auto"&gt;&lt;polygon points="0 0, 10 3.5, 0 7" fill="#475569" /&gt;&lt;/marker&gt;&lt;/defs&gt;&lt;rect width="350" height="100" fill="#f8fafc" rx="10" stroke="#e2e8f0" stroke-width="2"/&gt;&lt;text x="50" y="65" font-family="monospace" font-size="48" font-weight="bold" fill="#1e293b"&gt;y = mx + b&lt;/text&gt;&lt;path d="M125 75 Q125 100 100 105" fill="none" stroke="#3b82f6" stroke-width="2" marker-end="url(#arrowhead-systems-blog)"/&gt;&lt;text x="35" y="115" fill="#3b82f6" font-size="14" font-weight="bold"&gt;Slope (Rise/Run)&lt;/text&gt;&lt;path d="M255 75 Q255 100 280 105" fill="none" stroke="#ef4444" stroke-width="2" marker-end="url(#arrowhead-systems-blog)"/&gt;&lt;text x="228" y="115" fill="#ef4444" font-size="14" font-weight="bold"&gt;Y-Intercept (Start)&lt;/text&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;The "Slope-Intercept" formula is your map legend!&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;m&lt;/strong&gt; is your slope (the &amp;ldquo;path&amp;rdquo; or steepness).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;b&lt;/strong&gt; is your y-intercept (the &amp;ldquo;starting line&amp;rdquo;).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Step 2: Plot the Lines&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="step-2-plot-the-lines"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#step-2-plot-the-lines" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Start at the &lt;strong&gt;b&lt;/strong&gt; value on the vertical axis. Then, use the &lt;strong&gt;slope (Rise over Run)&lt;/strong&gt; to find your next point. Connect them to make a perfectly straight line.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Step 3: Find the &amp;ldquo;X&amp;rdquo;&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="step-3-find-the-x"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#step-3-find-the-x" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Look for the exact spot where the lines crash into each other. Write down the &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;span class="katex-mathml"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator="true"&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;(x, y)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"&gt;&lt;span class="base"&gt;&lt;span class="strut" style="height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mopen"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord mathnormal"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mpunct"&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.1667em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right:0.03588em;"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mclose"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; coordinates of that point.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div align="center"&gt;
&lt;svg width="300" height="300" viewBox="0 0 200 200" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" style="background:#f9f9f9;border:1px solid #ccc;border-radius:8px;" role="img" aria-label="Graph showing the intersection of y equals x plus 2 and y equals 2x"&gt;
&lt;path d="M0 100 h200 M100 0 v200" stroke="#ddd" stroke-width="2"/&gt;
&lt;path d="M0 20 h200 M0 40 h200 M0 60 h200 M0 80 h200 M0 120 h200 M0 140 h200 M0 160 h200 M0 180 h200" stroke="#eee" stroke-width="1"/&gt;
&lt;path d="M20 0 v200 M40 0 v200 M60 0 v200 M80 0 v200 M120 0 v200 M140 0 v200 M160 0 v200 M180 0 v200" stroke="#eee" stroke-width="1"/&gt;
&lt;line x1="60" y1="100" x2="160" y2="0" stroke="#3b82f6" stroke-width="3"/&gt;
&lt;text x="10" y="70" fill="#3b82f6" font-size="10" font-weight="bold"&gt;Alex: y = x + 2&lt;/text&gt;
&lt;line x1="100" y1="100" x2="150" y2="0" stroke="#ef4444" stroke-width="3"/&gt;
&lt;text x="110" y="115" fill="#ef4444" font-size="10" font-weight="bold"&gt;Sam: y = 2x&lt;/text&gt;
&lt;circle cx="140" cy="20" r="5" fill="#10b981"/&gt;
&lt;text x="145" y="35" fill="#059669" font-size="12" font-weight="bold"&gt;(2, 4)&lt;/text&gt;
&lt;/svg&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Figure 1: Sam catches up to Alex at the 2-mile mark (x=2), 4 miles from the entrance (y=4).&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;🔮 Visualizing the &amp;ldquo;Three Fates&amp;rdquo;&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="-visualizing-the-three-fates"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#-visualizing-the-three-fates" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;When you put two lines on a graph, only three things can happen. We call these the &lt;strong&gt;Three Fates&lt;/strong&gt; of a system:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;1. The Great Collision (One Solution)&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="1-the-great-collision-one-solution"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#1-the-great-collision-one-solution" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Most lines cross at exactly one point. This &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;span class="katex-mathml"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator="true"&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;(x, y)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"&gt;&lt;span class="base"&gt;&lt;span class="strut" style="height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mopen"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord mathnormal"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mpunct"&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.1667em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right:0.03588em;"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mclose"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; coordinate is the &lt;strong&gt;only&lt;/strong&gt; pair that works for both equations.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div align="center"&gt;
&lt;svg width="200" height="200" viewBox="0 0 100 100" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" role="img" aria-label="Two lines intersecting at one point"&gt;
&lt;rect width="100" height="100" fill="#f0fdf4" rx="8"/&gt;
&lt;path d="M0 50 h100 M50 0 v100" stroke="#cbd5e1" stroke-width="1"/&gt;
&lt;line x1="20" y1="80" x2="80" y2="20" stroke="#10b981" stroke-width="3"/&gt;
&lt;line x1="20" y1="20" x2="80" y2="80" stroke="#10b981" stroke-width="3"/&gt;
&lt;circle cx="50" cy="50" r="4" fill="#059669"/&gt;
&lt;/svg&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;One Solution:&lt;/b&gt; The lines intersect.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;2. The Parallel Paradox (No Solution)&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="2-the-parallel-paradox-no-solution"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#2-the-parallel-paradox-no-solution" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Lines with the same slope but different starting points are like train tracks. They travel together but &lt;strong&gt;never&lt;/strong&gt; touch.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div align="center"&gt;
&lt;svg width="200" height="200" viewBox="0 0 100 100" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" role="img" aria-label="Two parallel lines with no intersection"&gt;
&lt;rect width="100" height="100" fill="#fef2f2" rx="8"/&gt;
&lt;path d="M0 50 h100 M50 0 v100" stroke="#cbd5e1" stroke-width="1"/&gt;
&lt;line x1="20" y1="40" x2="80" y2="40" stroke="#ef4444" stroke-width="3"/&gt;
&lt;line x1="20" y1="60" x2="80" y2="60" stroke="#ef4444" stroke-width="3"/&gt;
&lt;/svg&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;No Solution:&lt;/b&gt; The lines are parallel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;3. The Secret Identity (Infinite Solutions)&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="3-the-secret-identity-infinite-solutions"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#3-the-secret-identity-infinite-solutions" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Sometimes, two equations turn out to be the exact same line. Since they are the same path, every single point on the line is a &amp;ldquo;meeting point.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div align="center"&gt;
&lt;svg width="200" height="200" viewBox="0 0 100 100" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" role="img" aria-label="Two identical overlapping lines"&gt;
&lt;rect width="100" height="100" fill="#eff6ff" rx="8"/&gt;
&lt;path d="M0 50 h100 M50 0 v100" stroke="#cbd5e1" stroke-width="1"/&gt;
&lt;line x1="20" y1="80" x2="80" y2="20" stroke="#3b82f6" stroke-width="5" stroke-dasharray="8,2"/&gt;
&lt;line x1="20" y1="80" x2="80" y2="20" stroke="#1d4ed8" stroke-width="2"/&gt;
&lt;/svg&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Infinite Solutions:&lt;/b&gt; They are the same line.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;📂 The Worksheet Mission Gallery&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="-the-worksheet-mission-gallery"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#-the-worksheet-mission-gallery" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Ready to start your training? Below is our &lt;strong&gt;Mission Gallery&lt;/strong&gt;. We have organized 10 different worksheets into a &amp;ldquo;Path to Mastery.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
