&lt;h2&gt;❓ Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="-frequently-asked-questions-faq"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#-frequently-asked-questions-faq" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Q: Can a system of linear equations have exactly two solutions?&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;A:&lt;/strong&gt; No! Linear equations are straight lines. Two straight lines can only cross once, never, or be the exact same line. They can&amp;rsquo;t &amp;ldquo;curve back&amp;rdquo; to hit each other a second time.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Q: Which method is the most accurate?&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;A:&lt;/strong&gt; While graphing is the most visual, &lt;strong&gt;Substitution&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;Elimination&lt;/strong&gt; are usually more accurate. Why? Because if the lines cross at a messy fraction like &lt;span class="katex"&gt;&lt;span class="katex-mathml"&gt;&lt;math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2.34&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo separator="true"&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;−&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1.98&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo stretchy="false"&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding="application/x-tex"&gt;(2.34, -1.98)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"&gt;&lt;span class="base"&gt;&lt;span class="strut" style="height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mopen"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord"&gt;2.34&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mpunct"&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.1667em;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord"&gt;−&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mord"&gt;1.98&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mclose"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, it&amp;rsquo;s almost impossible to see that perfectly on a graph!&lt;/p&gt;
